	<p>From funding to savings, these brilliant companies create solutions that move people and companies forward. </p><p>. <a></a>has created a fund that targets design-focused but scalable companies solving some of the world’s biggest problems.</p><p>. Users of <a></a>, a personal savings app, set spending rules for themselves. When they break those rules, money is automatically placed into savings.</p><p> makes investing accessible: For $500, invest in one of its funds. Its “pay what is fair” model gives customers the option to choose zero fees. </p><p>Online credit marketplace <a></a> helps VC-less startups snag small investments from trusted enders. It takes a 1 to 3 percent fee from lenders (rather than tax borrowers) and has helped secure $140 million for more than 2,500 businesses. </p><p> helps refinance those dreaded student loans by using career and financial histories to determine a borrower’s ability to pay, and saves borrowers an average of $18,000 over 10 years. </p><p>Microfinance startup <a></a> uses prepaid mobile-phone payment histories to quickly and affordably predict credit risk for borrowers in developing markets. </p><p>, an Israel-based equity crowdfunding platform, helps international private investors access early-stage opportunities alongside Israel’s leading angels. </p><p> helps freelancers save for tax season, automatically putting away the proper amount before payments route to a checking account. </p><p>New to investing? <a></a> turns stock data into simple, helpful graphics.</p><p>, which recently closed a $15 million Series B round, wants to make sharing money with friends (and paying brands) as easy as texting.  </p><h3>Check out more companies on the <a>2016 Brilliant 100 list</a>. </h3>

	
				
				
